</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="102" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="102.[151,1437,741,1991]" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1389,1415]" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haig" authorityYear="1960" box="[325,541,1389,1415]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilii">
<emphasis box="[325,541,1389,1415]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Petrolisthes nobilii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is phylogenetically close to the western Atlantic 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gray, 1831)" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[1118,1381,1389,1415]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="politus">
<emphasis box="[1118,1224,1389,1415]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">P. politus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gray, J. E." box="[1243,1373,1389,1415]" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" pagination="14 - 16" refId="ref72422" refString="Gray, J. E. (1831) Description of the species of Porcellana, in the collection of the British Museum. The Zoological Miscellany, 1, 14 - 16." type="journal article" year="1831">Gray, 1831</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(see below), these two taxa sharing the carapace being broadest in its posterior portion and lacking epibranchial tooth. However, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[266,373,1461,1488]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="politus">
<emphasis box="[266,283,1462,1487]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[297,373,1461,1487]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">politus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haig" authorityYear="1960" box="[519,619,1461,1487]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilii">
<emphasis box="[519,619,1461,1487]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">P. nobilii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by several characters, such as the absence of a narrow line of pubescence on the proximal half of the P1 palm and the gape of the P1 fingers usually without pubescence or with pubescence on only one of the chelipeds (
<bibRefCitation author="Haig, J." box="[476,598,1533,1560]" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" pagination="1 - 440" refId="ref72816" refString="Haig, J. (1960) The Porcellanidae (Crustacea: Anomura) of the Eastern Pacific. Allan Hancock Pacific Expedition, 24, 1 - 440." type="journal article" year="1960">Haig 1960</bibRefCitation>
). Among the eastern Pacific taxa, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haig" authorityYear="1960" box="[974,1074,1533,1559]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilii">
<emphasis box="[974,1074,1533,1559]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">P. nobilii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be most closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Gibbes" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[180,299,1570,1595]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armatus">
<emphasis box="[180,299,1570,1595]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">P. armatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, occupying much the same ecological niche as the latter species; in fact, the two species may often be found syntopically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="102.[151,1437,741,1991]" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">
The colour pattern of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haig" authorityYear="1960" box="[439,539,1641,1667]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilii">
<emphasis box="[439,539,1641,1667]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">P. nobilii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be consistent throughout its range, despite some variation, especially in younger individuals (
<figureCitation box="[388,524,1677,1704]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 63" captionStart-1="FIGURE 64" captionStart-2="FIGURE 65" captionStartId-0="103.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionStartId-1="104.[151,250,1560,1584]" captionStartId-2="105.[151,250,1720,1744]" captionTargetBox-0="[179,1407,181,1920]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1436,181,1536]" captionTargetBox-2="[151,1435,181,1696]" captionTargetId-0="figure-19@103.[179,1407,181,1920]" captionTargetId-1="figure-19@104.[151,1436,181,1536]" captionTargetId-2="figure-19@105.[151,1435,181,1696]" captionTargetPageId-0="103" captionTargetPageId-1="104" captionTargetPageId-2="105" captionText-0="FIGURE 63. Petrolisthes nobilii Haig, 1960: A, B, male (cl 10.6 mm, cw 10.2 mm) from Las Perlas Islands, Panama (MZUSP 33888), dorsal (A) and ventral (B) views [photographs by AA]." captionText-1="FIGURE 64. Petrolisthes nobilii Haig, 1960: A, ovigerous female (cl 6.3 mm cw 6.4 mm) from Azuero Peninunsula, Panama (FLMNH UF 57715), dorsal view [photograph by AA]; B, female (cl cw indet.) from Chame Bay, Panama (ULLZ/USNM), dorsal view [photograph courtesy of Justin Scioli]." captionText-2="FIGURE 65. Petrolisthes nobilii Haig, 1960: A–C, male from Nayarit, Mexico (CNCR), dorsal (A), ventral (B) and frontal (C) views [photographs courtesy of Luis Daniel Santana Moreno]." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5532365" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5532367" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5532371" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5532365/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5532367/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/5532371/files/figure.png" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Figs. 63–65</figureCitation>
). The most diagnostic features of the colouration of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haig" authorityYear="1960" box="[1100,1199,1677,1703]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilii">
<emphasis box="[1100,1199,1677,1703]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">P. nobilii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the dark greenish or green-brown carapace speckled with small yellowish dots and larger dark brown dots, and the similarly speckled meri of the ambulatory legs (P2–P4); their propodi, however, banded with brown and white. The chelipeds (P1) can be speckled in younger individuals or more uniform dark purplish-green in adults. Some young crabs may have a Π-shaped white patch on the carapace (
<figureCitation box="[595,700,1821,1848]" captionStart="FIGURE 64" captionStartId="104.[151,250,1560,1584]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1536]" captionTargetId="figure-19@104.[151,1436,181,1536]" captionTargetPageId="104" captionText="FIGURE 64. Petrolisthes nobilii Haig, 1960: A, ovigerous female (cl 6.3 mm cw 6.4 mm) from Azuero Peninunsula, Panama (FLMNH UF 57715), dorsal view [photograph by AA]; B, female (cl cw indet.) from Chame Bay, Panama (ULLZ/USNM), dorsal view [photograph courtesy of Justin Scioli]." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5532367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5532367/files/figure.png" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Fig. 64A</figureCitation>
). The specimen from the Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[1076,1190,1821,1847]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">California</collectingRegion>
illustrated by García- Madrigal &amp; Andréu-Sánchez (2009) photographed 
<emphasis box="[729,871,1858,1883]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">post-mortem</emphasis>
is clearly discoloured; however, the characteristic dark spots of the carapace remain clearly visible. In respect to colour pattern, the Mexican specimens (
<figureCitation box="[1344,1428,1893,1920]" captionStart="FIGURE 65" captionStartId="105.[151,250,1720,1744]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1696]" captionTargetId="figure-19@105.[151,1435,181,1696]" captionTargetPageId="105" captionText="FIGURE 65. Petrolisthes nobilii Haig, 1960: A–C, male from Nayarit, Mexico (CNCR), dorsal (A), ventral (B) and frontal (C) views [photographs courtesy of Luis Daniel Santana Moreno]." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5532371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5532371/files/figure.png" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Fig. 65</figureCitation>
) are very similar to the Panamanian specimens (
<figureCitation box="[691,775,1929,1955]" captionStart="FIGURE 63" captionStartId="103.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[179,1407,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-19@103.[179,1407,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="103" captionText="FIGURE 63. Petrolisthes nobilii Haig, 1960: A, B, male (cl 10.6 mm, cw 10.2 mm) from Las Perlas Islands, Panama (MZUSP 33888), dorsal (A) and ventral (B) views [photographs by AA]." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5532365" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5532365/files/figure.png" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Fig. 63</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[789,820,1929,1956]" captionStart="FIGURE 65" captionStartId="105.[151,250,1720,1744]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1696]" captionTargetId="figure-19@105.[151,1435,181,1696]" captionTargetPageId="105" captionText="FIGURE 65. Petrolisthes nobilii Haig, 1960: A–C, male from Nayarit, Mexico (CNCR), dorsal (A), ventral (B) and frontal (C) views [photographs courtesy of Luis Daniel Santana Moreno]." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5532371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5532371/files/figure.png" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">65</figureCitation>
), suggesting that they belong to the same, widespread species.
</paragraph>
